dPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus=\"pubmed\"><Year>2026</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>13</Day><Hour>6</Hour><Minute>39</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus=\"entrez\"><Year>2026</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>13</Day><Hour>0</Hour><Minute>43</Minute></PubMedPubDate></History><PublicationStatus>aheadofprint</PublicationStatus><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">42286839</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"doi\">10.1002/mus.70310</ArticleId></ArticleIdList><ReferenceList><Reference><Citation>S. A. Goutman, O. Hardiman, A. Al&#x2010;Chalabi, et&#xa0;al., &#x201c;Recent Advances in the Diagnosis and Prognosis of Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis,&#x201d; Lancet Neurology 21, no. 5 (2022): 480&#x2013;493.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>M. Garret, K. Mehta, J. Y. Chen, and S. Babu, &#x201c;Rise of the Genomic Medicine Era in Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis,&#x201d; Practical Neurology 22, no. 6 (2023): 22&#x2013;27.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>T. M. Miller, M. E. Cudkowicz, A. Genge, et&#xa0;al., &#x201c;Trial of Antisense Oligonucleotide Tofersen for SOD1 ALS,&#x201d; New England Journal of Medicine 387, no. 12 (2022): 1099&#x2013;1110.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>J. L. Cerillo and P. M. Tofersen, StatPearls (Treasure Island (FL), 2025).</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>T. M. Miller, M. E. Cudkowicz, P. J. Shaw, et&#xa0;al., &#x201c;Long&#x2010;Term Tofersen in SOD1 Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis,&#x201d; JAMA Neurology 83 (2025): e254946, https://doi.org/10.1001/jamaneurol.2025.4946.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>C. Quinn, E. A. Macklin, N. Atassi, et&#xa0;al., &#x201c;Post&#x2010;Lumbar Puncture Headache Is Reduced With Use of Atraumatic Needles in ALS,&#x201d; Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis &amp; Frontotemporal Degeneration 14, no. 7&#x2013;8 (2013): 632&#x2013;634, https://doi.org/10.3109/21678421.2013.808227.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>M. Yerton, A. Winter, D. Gelevski, et&#xa0;al., &#x201c;Expanded Access Protocol (EAP) Program for Access to Investigational Products for Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS),&#x201d; Muscle &amp; Nerve 67, no. 6 (2023): 456&#x2013;463.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>M. Huang, Y. U. Liu, X. Yao, D. Qin, and H. Su, &#x201c;Variability in SOD1&#x2010;Associated Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis: Geographic Patterns, Clinical Heterogeneity, Molecular Alterations, and Therapeutic Implications,&#x201d; Translational Neurodegeneration 13 (2024): 28, https://doi.org/10.1186/s40035&#x2010;024&#x2010;00416&#x2010;x.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>M. Benatar, J. Wuu, P. M. Andersen, et&#xa0;al., &#x201c;Design of a Randomized, Placebo&#x2010;Controlled, Phase 3 Trial of Tofersen Initiated in Clinically Presymptomatic SOD1 Variant Carriers: The ATLAS Study,&#x201d; Neurotherapeutics 19, no. 4 (2022): 1248&#x2013;1258, https://doi.org/10.1007/s13311&#x2010;022&#x2010;01237&#x2010;4.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>T. Bali, W. Self, J. Liu, et&#xa0;al., &#x201c;Defining SOD1 ALS Natural History to Guide Therapeutic Clinical Trial Design,&#x201d; Journal of Neurology, Neurosurgery, and Psychiatry 88, no. 2 (2017): 99&#x2013;105, https://doi.org/10.1136/jnnp&#x2010;2016&#x2010;313521.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>P. A. Hudgins, A. J. Fountain, P. R. Chapman, and L. M. Shah, &#x201c;Difficult Lumbar Puncture: Pitfalls and Tips From the Trenches,&#x201d; AJNR. American Journal of Neuroradiology 38, no. 7 (2017): 1276&#x2013;1283.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>M. Gerasymchuk, J. C. Durieux, and A. P. Nayate, &#x201c;Why, How Often, and What Happens When we Fail: A Retrospective Analysis of Failed Fluoroscopically Guided Lumbar Punctures,&#x201d; AJNR. American Journal of Neuroradiology 44, no. 6 (2023): 722&#x2013;729.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>S. Engelborghs, E. Niemantsverdriet, H. Struyfs, et&#xa0;al., &#x201c;Consensus Guidelines for Lumbar Puncture in Patients With Neurological Diseases,&#x201d; Alzheimer's &amp; Dementia 18, no. 8 (2017): 111&#x2013;126, https://doi.org/10.1016/j.dadm.2017.04.007.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>US Food and Drug Food Administration, FDA Approves Treatment of Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis Associated With a Mutation in the SOD1 Gene (FDA, 2023).</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>D. Gelevski, G. Addy, M. Rohrer, et&#xa0;al., &#x201c;Safety and Activity of Anti&#x2010;CD14 Antibody IC14 (Atibuclimab) in ALS: Experience With Expanded Access Protocol,&#x201d; Muscle &amp; Nerve 67, no. 5 (2023): 354&#x2013;362.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>G. Addy, E. Scirocco, D. Gelevski, et&#xa0;al., &#x201c;An Expanded Access Protocol of RNS60 in Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis,&#x201d; Muscle &amp; Nerve 72 (2025): 124&#x2013;129.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>D. V. Neel, C. Baselga&#x2010;Garriga, M. Benson, et&#xa0;al., &#x201c;Multicenter Expanded Access Program for Access to Investigational Products for Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis,&#x201d; Muscle &amp; Nerve 70, no. 2 (2024): 232&#x2013;239.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>Office, &#x201c;ACT for ALS. U.S. Food and Drug Administration,&#x201d; Published 2024, https://www.fda.gov/industry/medical&#x2010;products&#x2010;rare&#x2010;diseases&#x2010;and&#x2010;conditions/accelerating&#x2010;access&#x2010;critical&#x2010;therapies&#x2010;als&#x2010;act&#x2010;act&#x2010;als.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>M. Yerton, A. Winter, A. Kostov, et&#xa0;al., &#x201c;An Expanded Access Protocol of RT001 in Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis&#x2014;Initial Experience With a Lipid Peroxidation Inhibitor,&#x201d; Muscle &amp; Nerve 66, no. 4 (2022): 421&#x2013;425, https://doi.org/10.1002/mus.27672.</Citation></Reference></ReferenceList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status=\"Publisher\" Owner=\"NLM\"><PMID Version=\"1\">42287757</PMID><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>13</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel=\"Print-Electronic\"><Journal><ISSN IssnType=\"Electronic\">1950-6007</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium=\"Internet\"><Volume>201</Volume><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Jun</Month><Day>13</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Biomedicine &amp; pharmacotherapy = Biomedecine &amp; pharmacotherapie</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Biomed Pharmacother</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Focused ultrasound-mediated nanocarrier delivery across the blood-brain barrier for neurodegenerative diseases.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>119622</StartPage><MedlinePgn>119622</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType=\"doi\" ValidYN=\"Y\">10.1016/j.biopha.2026.119622</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType=\"pii\" ValidYN=\"Y\">S0753-3322(26)00658-X</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>The development of effective therapies for neurodegenerative disorders such as Alzheimer's disease, Parkinson's disease, Huntington's disease, and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis remains a major challenge due to the restrictive nature of the blood-brain barrier (BBB). Conventional systemic drug delivery strategies often fail to achieve sufficient central nervous system (CNS) penetration while avoiding peripheral toxicity. Focused ultrasound (FUS), particularly when combined with microbubbles or nanocarriers, has emerged as a non-invasive approach to transiently and precisely open the BBB, enabling targeted delivery of therapeutics to the brain parenchyma. This review provides a comprehensive overview of the mechanisms by which FUS enhances CNS drug delivery, with a dedicated focus on its integration with nanoparticle-based systems, including liposomes, polymeric nanoparticles, dendrimers, metallic nanoparticles, and exosomes. We discuss how these nanocarriers can be engineered for improved stability, targeting specificity, and stimulus-responsive release upon FUS exposure. Recent advances in ultrasound technology, image guidance (particularly MRI), and therapeutic formulations are summarized, along with preclinical and clinical evidence across key neurodegenerative conditions. Despite promising results, several challenges remain, including long-term BBB stability, regulatory standardization, and scalability for broad clinical application. By integrating principles from acoustics, pharmacology, and nanotechnology, FUS-mediated drug delivery, especially in combination with smart nano systems, represents a significant advancement in precision neurotherapeutics, offering new hope for previously untreatable CNS diseases.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2026. Published by Elsevier Masson SAS.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN=\"Y\"><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Jaberi</LastName><ForeName>Khojaste Rahimi</ForeName><Initials>KR</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Neuroscience, School of Advanced Medical Sciences and Technologies, Shiraz University of Medical Sciences, Shiraz, Iran.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Haghighi</LastName><ForeName>Maryam Rohani</ForeName><Initials>MR</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Clinical Neurology Research Center, School of Medicine, Shiraz University of Medical Sciences, Shiraz, Iran.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Aligholi</LastName><ForeName>Hadi</ForeName><Initials>H</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Neuroscience, School of Advanced Medical Sciences and Technologies, Shiraz University of Medical Sciences, Shiraz, Iran.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Takallu</LastName><ForeName>Sara</ForeName><Initials>S</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Nanotechnology, School of Advanced Medical Sciences and Technologies, Shiraz University of Medical Sciences, Shiraz, Iran.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Asadi</LastName><ForeName>Peyman</ForeName><Initials>P</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Nanotechnology, School of Advanced Medical Sciences and Technologies, Shiraz University of Medical Sciences, Shiraz, Iran.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Mirzaei</LastName><ForeName>Esmaeil</ForeName><Initials>E</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Nanotechnology, School of Advanced Medical Sciences and Technologies, Shiraz University of Medical Sciences, Shiraz, Iran. Electronic address: e_mirzaei@sums.ac.ir.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Jaberi</LastName><ForeName>Abbas Rahimi</ForeName><Initials>AR</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Neuroscience, School of Advanced Medical Sciences and Technologies, Shiraz University of Medical Sciences, Shiraz, Iran; Clinical Neurology Research Center, School of Medicine, Shiraz University of Medical Sciences, Shiraz, Iran. Electronic address: rahimeia@sums.com.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Sahraian</LastName><ForeName>Ali</ForeName><Initials>A</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Psychiatry, School of Medicine, Shiraz University of Medical Sciences, Shiraz, Iran. Electronic address: sahraianali5@sums.ac.ir.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI=\"D016428\">Journal Article</PublicationType><PublicationType UI=\"D016454\">Review</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType=\"Electronic\"><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>13</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>France</Country><MedlineTA>Biomed Pharmacother</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>8213295</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>0753-3322</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo><CitationSubset>IM</CitationSubset><KeywordList Owner=\"NOTNLM\"><Keyword MajorTopicYN=\"N\">CNS therapeutics</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN=\"N\">Focused ultrasound</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN=\"N\">Nanoparticle drug delivery</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN=\"N\">Neurodegenerative diseases</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN=\"N\">Ultrasound-mediated delivery</Keyword></KeywordList><CoiStatement>Declaration of Competing Interest The author(s) declare that this review was conducted in the absence of any commercial or financial relationships that could be construed as a potential conflict of interest.</CoiStatement></MedlineCitation><PubmedData><History><PubMedPubDate PubStatus=\"received\"><Year>2026</Year><Month>1</Month><Day>31</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus=\"revised\"><Year>2026</Year><Month>5</Month><Day>16</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus=\"accepted\"><Year>2026</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>4</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus=\"medline\"><Year>2026</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>15</Day><Hour>11</Hour><Minute>30</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus=\"pubmed\"><Year>2026</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>15</Day><Hour>11</Hour><Minute>30</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus=\"entrez\"><Year>2026</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>13</Day><Hour>17</Hour><Minute>59</Minute></PubMedPubDate></History><PublicationStatus>aheadofprint</PublicationStatus><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">42287757</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"doi\">10.1016/j.biopha.2026.119622</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pii\">S0753-3322(26)00658-X</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle>\n<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status=\"Publisher\" Owner=\"NLM\"><PMID Version=\"1\">42288493</PMID><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>13</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel=\"Print-Electronic\"><Journal><ISSN IssnType=\"Electronic\">2052-4463</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium=\"Internet\"><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Jun</Month><Day>13</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Scientific data</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Sci Data</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Quantitative Proteomics Unveils Comprehensive Tissue-Specific VCP Interaction Networks in Mice.</ArticleTitle><ELocationID EIdType=\"doi\" ValidYN=\"Y\">10.1038/s41597-026-07626-0</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>Valosin-containing protein (VCP), a conserved AAA ATPase hexamer, participates in multiple biological processes including ERAD, ubiquitin-dependent degradation by extracting misfolded proteins for proteasomal degradation. Although its interactions with cofactors are well-characterized, and its dysregulation is implicated in multisystem proteinopathy, amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, and cancer, the tissue-specific VCP interactomes underlying its functional versatility remain elusive. Here, we generated HA-N-tagged VCP knock-in mice via CRISPR/Cas9 strategy and performed affinity purification coupled with data-independent acquisition (DIA) mass spectrometry to systematically profile VCP interactors across eight mouse tissues, yielding a high-confidence dataset. We identified 923 robust VCP-binding partners, including established interactors (UBX2B, UFD1, proteasomal subunits) and novel candidates implicated in energy metabolism (TCA cycle, oxidative phosphorylation) and protein quality control (proteasome, ERAD). Notably, we validated the interaction of VCP to two hepatic candidate proteins, DAXX and PRKAG2 (AMPK &#x3b3;2 regulatory subunit), using HepG2 cells. This study establishes the first in vivo atlas of the VCP interaction network, providing mechanistic insights into its tissue-specific roles and highlighting potential therapeutic avenues for VCP-related disorders.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>&#xa9; 2026. The Author(s).</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN=\"Y\"><Author ValidYN=\"Y\" EqualContrib=\"Y\"><LastName>Wang</LastName><ForeName>Nannan</ForeName><Initials>N</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Laboratory Medicine, Nanjing Drum Tower Hospital, The Affiliated Hospital of Nanjing Universi